Here is a brief summary of the principles of them.<br>
No specific atomic weapon designs are presented here :<br>
only general the principles for their assembly. You decide which atomic pit designs  would be most appropriate for use on an orion nuclear fission pulse rocket for yourselves.<br>
<br>
1. solid core christy device : The core is compressed into a supercritical density  by  placing it in the center of a detonating hollow sphere of high explosive, or by placing it in<br>
the center of 3 rows of from 4-6 overlapping symmetrical high explosive charges that create converging shock waves on the pit at the center.Testted by Us. 1945, and 1946*<br>
<br>
2. A Hollow core spherical pit placed in the center of the high<br>
explosive assemblys mentioned above in 1. It Functions  in the same way as number 1.Here a hollow metal neutron source is used.Tested by U.S. 1953*<br>
<br>
3. One directional,bidirectional and mutidirectional gun type<br>
atomic weapon core assemblys.(the origional littleboy device<br>
and also the more advanced versions of him are grouped<br>
collectively here)Tested by U.S. 1945 and later tests.<br>
<br>
4. Levitated pit : hollow wedge core design , :A solid sphere<br>
of fissile material is devided into 4 or more equal/symetrical<br>
wedges wielded on the inside of the hollow tamper sphere<br>
inside of a spherical vacume cavity. The high explosive  compression of the core blows, and compresses the pieces into a common ball of critical mass in the center of the spherical vacume cavity , by making it more, compact and more dense. Tested by the british 1952*and by U.S 1948*<br>
<br>
5. Solid Wedges of fissile material are wielded between the inside of a hollow spherical tamper and a solid metal  neutron<br>
source. The detonation of high explosive shaped  charges <br>
crushes the fissile wedges onto the neutron source, and merges them into a common ball of critical mass by making the core more compact, and more dense,<br>
:B . Or hollow fissile metal  cones can be used in place of solid fissile wedges  in this design configuration.<br>
*These or similar devices: Probably tested in operation plumb bob 1957-1959 by U.S..<br>
<br>
6. Linear implosion: a barely subcritical oval shaped mass of fissile material is crushed into a solid spherical super critical mass by exploding a hollow cylinder of high explosive around it.<br>
* Tested by U.S. circa 1970<br>
7. Cylindrical implosion : a hollow or solid cylinder of fissile<br>
material is crushed into a supercrital solid cylinder by exploding a hollow cylinder of high explosive around it.<br>
*Tested by U.S; operation greenhouse 1951<br>
